# What is the Unison structure mapping

## Introduction

Structure mapping is the process of writing descriptions on how to transfer data from the source data structure to the target data structure. It means that you should make relations between source and target tables and fields. 

There is two type of the rules:

- **Mapping rules** with descriptions on how to do transferring and transforming the data.   
- **Data extraction rules** with short SQL scripts that provide data transfering. 

By default Unison doesn't transform source data to the second dataset. It just using your scripts to transform the data on fly when you are:

- Doing an export data to the target CDM  
- Using Unison for writing queries and getting cohorts of the patients based on target CDM

It’s important to remember while you are using Unison. 

## Interface overview

![][image1]

**Source tables**   
Show structure of the source database. Available to expand the tree and drill down from the table view to the field view. Possible to select table or custom set of fields from the different tables and see details in source explorer and mapping rules sections. Names if the tables can be used in joins and data extraction rules sections.

**Source explorer**   
Section with detailed information about chosen source table / source column(s). Contain:

1. name of the chosen field(s)  
2. values distribution in the source field  
3. domain suggestions \- what domain unison can suggest to the user. suggestions based on the algorithm that analyse source values and try to find correct concepts, get domains from suggested values.  
4. mapped CDM entities \- mapped CDM entities for selected source fields.

**Mapping rules**  
Section that should be filled by instructions on how to map source fields into CDM entities and fields.

**Data extraction rules**   
SQL rules (queries) how to transfer from the source tables to CDM tables.

**Joins**   
Intermediate tables that realised relations between source tables and preparing custom tables. 

**CDM tables**  
Show structure of the target CDM.

# Process details

## How to write a mapping rule

Mapping rule is the element of the documentation. It describes how each source field should be mapped to each CDM field. Data steward or domain expert describes it for the data engineer.

### Action map

1. (1) Explore source tables, look at the names of the tables and fields.  
2. (1) Select one table and look at the Source explorer section.  
3. (2) Look at the source values and domain suggestions.  
4. (3) Choose a target CDM entity.  
5. (4) Click on add button for adding new mapping rules for current source field.  
6. (5) Select the CDM field that should be the target for the current source field.  
7. (5) Write a description with an explanation how and why this source field should be mapped to the target entity's field.  
8. (6) Click save or cancel if you need more time to understand how to map it correctly. 

## How to create relations between source tables 

In every case when you are uploading a dataset to Unison, tables will be uploaded with all fields. But Unison can't automatically check what fields are relationships between tables and what are not. So user should build relations between source tables using the Joins section.

### Action map

**Relate to the patient table**

1. Find a table that you want to relate to the patient table in the "Source tables" section.  
2. Find a field in the table that is related to the patient table.  
3. Open the patient table.  
4. Find what the name of field with patient IDs is  
5. Click on "create join"  
6. Write in "Alias" field a name of the join (recommended name is the name of the table)  
7. Select "left table" as table with patients.  
8. Select "right table" as the table that you want to relate.  
9. Write an expression "$table1.\*name\_of\_the\_patient\_id\_field" \= $table2."name\_of\_the\_patient\_id\_field"  
10. Click on "save button"

**Relations between another tables**  
You can relate any tables only to already added tables.  
If you want to start using some table that has no relations to the patient table you need to find a related table which has relations to the patient table and also has relations to the required table.

Write relations for this intermediate table and then connect it to the required table with the same algorithm as for the patient table.

## How to write an extraction rule

Extraction rule is an SQL query that makes a connection between source field(s) and target CDM field. Using this SQL query Unison is getting source data and transforming it to the target field on the fly when you’re doing an export or execute query in the Unison cohort browser.

The Rules are based on CDM entities. Each rule contains a list of required**\*** and optional "fields" from the CDM entity. Required fields will be created automatically. Optional ones you may add as you need. 

When you have written an extraction rule for some CDM entity field, data from this rule begins to be used just in a value mapping immediately if it is marked as a vocabulary field. 

Data from the data extraction rule will be able to be used in the cohort api and export after all required fields will be published. 

After publishing data will be available in the federation tab. Data will be transformed while query will be executed. So you can continue to store your data in your source data structure and be able to transform it to any CDM in parallel.

### Action map

![][image3]

1. Look at the "Source tables" section.  
2. Select table with the mapping rules (count on the right side of the list).  
3. Explore the mapping rules section.  
4. Find mapped entities in the "CDM tables" section.  
5. Expand the "Data extraction rules" section.  
6. Click on an "add rule" button.

Person table is available by default, because the link to the person table is the setting of the runner. All other tables will be available for execution rules after the user creates relations between the source patient table and the source table required for execution. 

Created data extraction rules contain all required fields. Required fields are the fields required by the CDM. If you don’t have enough data for making extraction data for the all required fields you can't finish creating the data extraction rule.

So check the mapping rules before starting on availability of all required mapping rules. 

1. Expand list of the fields by clicking on the list item (in the example "person")  
2. Choose field for extraction and click on edit button  
3. Choose the join from which you want to extract the data. It might be joined with the source table or your custom table.  
4. Write a SQL expression for extracting. Full doc on how to write SQL in Unison expressions here, or you can look how it is realised at the demo dataset to figure out the principle.  
5. Click on the save button  
6. Click on the "play" button to get the data from the source and check the results. 

## Publishing

### Core principle

Publishing is an action that makes your data extraction rules work.   
It means that not published data extraction rules provide data just to value mapping.   
Usage being able after all the fields inside mapping rule and mapping rule will be published. 

Core rule: entity extraction rule being able to publish after all required fields have been published.  
![][image4]

### Action map for field publishing

![][image5]

1. Select the CDM entity and expand the “Data extraction rules” section.   
2. Select and expand the entity with data extraction rules.   
3. Choose the field for publishing and click on the edit button.  
4. Click on the publish button. 

### 

### Action map for entity publishing

![][image6]

1. Do the previous step for publishing each field in the data extraction rule.   
2. Click on edit button related with data extraction entity (2)  
3. Click the publish button
